ct property values. Lenders require appraisals from their approved appraiser lists rather than accepting buyer-ordered valuations due to independence requirements."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Should I buy land before getting construction loan approval?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Buying land before securing construction loan approval creates significant risk that should be avoided whenever possible. Buyers who purchase parcels assuming construction financing will materialize face potential financial disaster if lenders subsequently deny applications due to credit issues, appraisal problems, or builder qualification failures. These buyers get stuck owning land with ongoing property tax obligations but no financing path to intended construction, forcing either expensive carrying costs or distressed sales at losses."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What's better: buying land cash or financing?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Buying land with cash versus financing depends on opportunity cost considerations, alternative investment returns, tax planning, and overall financial strategy. Cash purchases eliminate interest expenses saving $30,000-$80,000 over 10-15 year holding periods on typical $150,000-$300,000 parcels. Additionally, cash buyers avoid origination fees, appraisal costs, and other financing expenses totaling 2-5% of purchase prices."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How do I compare different lot loan offers?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Comparing different lot loan offers requires analyzing total costs over full loan terms rather than focusing exclusively on interest rates or monthly payments. Two loans with identical rates might have dramatically different costs when one charges 2% origination fees while the other demands zero points. A lower-rate loan with expensive fees might cost more over short holding periods compared to higher-rate zero-fee alternatives."}}, {"@type": "Question", "na